      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Here are the results for the paper you searched for:\n\n## \"Is SGD a Bayesian sampler? Well, almost\"\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The paper is authored by **Chris Mingard, Guillermo Valle-Pérez, Joar Skalse, and Ard A. Louis**, and was published in the *Journal of Machine Learning Research* (JMLR), volume 22(79), pages 1–64, 2021."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n**Note:** The query mentioned \"Sherrington\" as an author, but this name does not appear among the authors. The actual co-author is **Joar Skalse**.\n\n### Summary of the Paper\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Overparameterised deep neural networks (DNNs) are highly expressive and can, in principle, generate almost any function that fits a training dataset with zero error. The vast majority of these functions will perform poorly on unseen data, and yet in practice DNNs often generalise remarkably well. This success suggests that a trained DNN must have a strong inductive bias towards functions with low generalisation error."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The authors empirically investigate this inductive bias by calculating the probability P_SGD(f|S) that an overparameterised DNN trained with SGD converges on a function f consistent with a training set S, and also use Gaussian processes to estimate the Bayesian posterior probability P_B(f|S)."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Their findings imply that strong inductive bias in the parameter-function map, rather than a special property of SGD, is the primary explanation for why DNNs generalise so well in the overparameterised regime."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n### Key Links\n- **JMLR**: https://jmlr.org/papers/v22/20-676.html\n- **arXiv**: https://arxiv.org/abs/2006.15191\n- **Oxford University Research Archive**: https://ora.ox.ac.uk/objects/uuid:632426cc-9a46-4a06-af4c-7b2d392bce12"
      }
